00:00:05.917 --> 00:00:08.250
CAROLINE DEHNERT MOYER: A lot
of people know what AA is.

00:00:08.250 --> 00:00:10.380
Just a moment about what
Al-Anon is because I don't

00:00:10.380 --> 00:00:12.300
think that's as well-known.

00:00:12.300 --> 00:00:16.140
Al-Anon is-- I call it
the sister program to AA.

00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:19.410
It's where if you have
a family member that's

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:22.650
struggling with alcoholism,
you join Al-Anon.

00:00:22.650 --> 00:00:23.430
We get together.

00:00:23.430 --> 00:00:27.900
We talk about our struggles
as family members.

00:00:27.900 --> 00:00:29.640
It was actually
founded by the wife

00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:31.890
of the guy that founded
AA, which I think

00:00:31.890 --> 00:00:35.760
is kind of fitting because I
think these really go together.

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:37.980
When they go together
well, it actually

00:00:37.980 --> 00:00:40.770
addresses the disease
better because it truly

00:00:40.770 --> 00:00:45.880
is a family addiction, and we'll
talk about what that means.

00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:48.240
But so here we are
talking about addiction.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:53.280
I'm going to tell a story about
my brother, who growing up he

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:54.908
became a crack cocaine addict.

00:00:54.908 --> 00:00:56.700
And then Jam's going
to talk about his road

00:00:56.700 --> 00:00:58.560
to recovery from
heroin addiction.

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:00.630
But just one other
little minute before we

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:04.140
get into the stories about how
we landed on this stage, which

00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:06.990
is kind of a couple of things
happened together, sort of

00:01:06.990 --> 00:01:08.710
like the perfect storm.

00:01:08.710 --> 00:01:10.530
The first was that
I actually started

00:01:10.530 --> 00:01:11.702
going to therapy myself.

00:01:11.702 --> 00:01:14.160
And I started going to therapy
a couple years ago because I

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:16.740
was just having, honestly,
a really hard time dealing

00:01:16.740 --> 00:01:21.090
with my brother and his needs
and what he was going through.

00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:22.770
I also have two
little kids and a mom.

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:24.180
And I was like, I can't--

00:01:24.180 --> 00:01:27.030
this is mercy.

00:01:27.030 --> 00:01:27.985
Please, somebody.

00:01:27.985 --> 00:01:29.610
My friend, who's in
the audience today,

00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:31.027
referred me to a
therapist, and it

00:01:31.027 --> 00:01:33.150
was one of the best
things I think that I did.

00:01:33.150 --> 00:01:34.810
So that happened a
couple of years ago.

00:01:34.810 --> 00:01:37.733
And she said, you need
to talk about this stuff.

00:01:37.733 --> 00:01:38.650
So that was one thing.

00:01:38.650 --> 00:01:39.630
The second thing--
I'm getting a little

00:01:39.630 --> 00:01:41.310
shout out to Sharon
if you're out there,

00:01:41.310 --> 00:01:43.170
my manager on
Livestream in New York.

00:01:43.170 --> 00:01:50.010
Sharon, thank you for nudging me
with the appropriate force to--

00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:52.830
she said, Caroline, you've been
here a long time at Google.

00:01:52.830 --> 00:01:54.705
You need to find
your voice again.

00:01:54.705 --> 00:01:57.330
And I was like, well, what does
that mean, find my voice again?

00:01:57.330 --> 00:02:00.540
Find something you really care
about outside of your core work

00:02:00.540 --> 00:02:01.230
responsibility.

00:02:01.230 --> 00:02:03.610
And probably everybody's
manager says that at some point.

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:06.960
So you go on to our internal
systems, and you're like,

00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:10.620
I'll become a coach or I'm
going to take this one on one

00:02:10.620 --> 00:02:12.960
class on allyship or whatever.

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:18.690
So I did that, and I was like,
this is not what Sharon means.

00:02:18.690 --> 00:02:20.640
And the third thing
that happened was I

00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:24.120
got an email from Ann, who
is one of the co-organizers

00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:26.040
of the conference today.

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:28.940
And she sent out a call
for speakers last December

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:31.440
or November saying hey, we want
to put on this mental health

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:33.150
conference in Chicago.

00:02:33.150 --> 00:02:34.690
Who wants to talk?

00:02:34.690 --> 00:02:37.570
And I was like, mmm, no.

00:02:37.570 --> 00:02:40.085
But then I was like,
OK, find my voice.

00:02:40.085 --> 00:02:41.460
Sharon wants me
to find my voice.

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:45.060
So I reached out to Ann,
and I was like, Ann,

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:47.880
what do people talk about
at these conferences?

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:49.708
And so she shared
some of the talks

00:02:49.708 --> 00:02:51.000
that people were going to give.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.950
And I read some of these things,
and I was like, holy shit,

00:02:55.950 --> 00:02:58.020
these are some brave
people to get up and talk

00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:01.428
about-- if anybody was here
yesterday, it was amazing,

00:03:01.428 --> 00:03:03.220
the stories that people
were talking about,

00:03:03.220 --> 00:03:06.150
and the stories afterwards in
the micro kitchens and stuff.

00:03:06.150 --> 00:03:08.280
So I already know that
we're touching people

00:03:08.280 --> 00:03:10.103
with this conference.

00:03:10.103 --> 00:03:11.520
The second thought,
though, that I

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:13.410
had after reading
that was oh my god,

00:03:13.410 --> 00:03:15.250
nobody's going to
talk about addiction.

00:03:15.250 --> 00:03:18.360
And we cannot have a mental
health conference in Chicago

00:03:18.360 --> 00:03:20.320
without somebody
talking about addiction.

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:22.890
And I was like shit,
I think I just found

00:03:22.890 --> 00:03:25.050
the voice that I need to find.

00:03:25.050 --> 00:03:26.370
It's there.

00:03:26.370 --> 00:03:27.660
It's gotta come out.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:31.330
And I was like, OK, Ann, I
think I can talk about this.

00:03:31.330 --> 00:03:33.540
And as soon as I did that,
I sent a text to this man,

00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:35.910
and I said hey,
Jam, you don't even

00:03:35.910 --> 00:03:39.648
know me at all because the rock
concert happened much later.

00:03:39.648 --> 00:03:41.190
I said you don't
even know me at all.

00:03:41.190 --> 00:03:46.860
But I've seen the talks you've
done at high schools to kids,

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:48.138
and it's powerful stuff.

00:03:48.138 --> 00:03:49.680
And people need to
hear your message.

00:03:49.680 --> 00:03:52.097
And I said this is a different
audience than a high school

00:03:52.097 --> 00:03:54.810
gym, I said, but I know I'm
not the only one with family

00:03:54.810 --> 00:03:56.250
members here at Google.

00:03:56.250 --> 00:03:58.583
Somebody came up to me in the
micro kitchen this morning

00:03:58.583 --> 00:04:01.050
and she said, I'm going to
be very touched by your talk

00:04:01.050 --> 00:04:03.675
because I have a brother that's
dealing with a heroin addiction

00:04:03.675 --> 00:04:04.250
right now.

00:04:04.250 --> 00:04:07.110
So thank you for
validating that I'm not

00:04:07.110 --> 00:04:08.990
the only one with
a family member.

00:04:08.990 --> 00:04:11.190
I said, I'm also not the
only parent here at Google

00:04:11.190 --> 00:04:14.010
that worries about our kids.

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:16.350
And I'm certainly not
the only one that--

00:04:16.350 --> 00:04:18.430
I know there are
people that struggle

00:04:18.430 --> 00:04:19.930
with their own
addictions at Google.

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:22.555
So I said please come do
this talk with me, Jam.

00:04:22.555 --> 00:04:24.180
In five seconds he's
like, I don't even

00:04:24.180 --> 00:04:25.950
know who you are, but yeah,
I'm going to come to your talk

00:04:25.950 --> 00:04:26.450
with you.

00:04:26.450 --> 00:04:27.580
It's like thank you.

00:04:27.580 --> 00:04:28.530
Thank you, you know?

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:32.530
So that is how we got
on this stage today.

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:35.250
And with that, I'm going
to go into my story which

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:36.930
starts with this picture here.

00:04:36.930 --> 00:04:39.490
This is going back
a long time ago.

00:04:39.490 --> 00:04:41.670
This is me, cute
little Caroline.

00:04:41.670 --> 00:04:44.470
This is my oldest brother
holding me, my twin brother,

00:04:44.470 --> 00:04:45.970
and my brother Carl
that we're going

00:04:45.970 --> 00:04:48.390
to be talking about today some.

00:04:48.390 --> 00:04:50.340
So this is what a
typical Sunday morning

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:52.770
looked like in our household.

00:04:52.770 --> 00:04:57.600
I grew up in Evanston, happy,
sort of middle class family.

00:04:57.600 --> 00:04:59.480
My parents were both musicians.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:02.580
You'll see there's a little
music theme going on today.

00:05:02.580 --> 00:05:06.400
And we would wake up
often on a Sunday morning.

00:05:06.400 --> 00:05:09.340
My dad played the trombone.

00:05:09.340 --> 00:05:13.360
And we were all required to
get our instruments out and jam

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:15.380
Sunday morning style.

00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:17.480
So this is kind of
what it looked like.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:22.030
And it was a very happy
household for a lot of years.

00:05:22.030 --> 00:05:23.500
We would do this Sunday morning.

00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:25.090
Then WWF would come on.

00:05:25.090 --> 00:05:27.472
We would do the "Hulk Hogan",
"Andre the Giant" thing,

00:05:27.472 --> 00:05:28.930
and then we would
watch the Chicago

00:05:28.930 --> 00:05:31.060
Bears lose at 12:00 Central.

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:34.810
JAM ALKER: Got a lot
of nodding heads here.

00:05:34.810 --> 00:05:37.270
CAROLINE DEHNERT MOYER: Yeah,
babies of the '70s here.

00:05:37.270 --> 00:05:40.520
And this was a very happy home.

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:43.010
And I say that because
I think a lot of times,

00:05:43.010 --> 00:05:45.490
people think addicts come
out of unhappy homes.

00:05:45.490 --> 00:05:48.290
And we'll hear a little bit
of a story about difficulty

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:49.270
in early years.

00:05:49.270 --> 00:05:54.400
But we had a very
happy home growing up.

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:57.340
But then comes high school.

00:05:57.340 --> 00:06:00.070
And if chapter one is like
happy home, chapter two

00:06:00.070 --> 00:06:01.660
it's called the diagnosis.

00:06:01.660 --> 00:06:05.965
And the diagnosis was my dad
being diagnosed with cancer.

00:06:05.965 --> 00:06:07.090
And I remember how it went.

00:06:07.090 --> 00:06:08.910
We're all the four of
us in the basement,

00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:12.070
you know, typical basement,
just junkyard toys,

00:06:12.070 --> 00:06:13.570
and we had a pool table.

00:06:13.570 --> 00:06:16.780
My mom and dad come down to the
basement, and they sit us down.

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:22.000
And my mom, it was, says kids,
we have something to tell you.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.580
Your father has been
diagnosed with cancer.

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:28.420
And we were like OK, we
know that word is terrible.

00:06:28.420 --> 00:06:30.580
And my brother Carl says--

00:06:30.580 --> 00:06:33.610
I remember this-- can't
they just cut it out,

00:06:33.610 --> 00:06:36.220
like surgically remove it?

00:06:36.220 --> 00:06:38.560
And of course, that was not
the kind of cancer he had.

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:41.350
So he started chemotherapy
the next week,

00:06:41.350 --> 00:06:47.270
and the chemotherapy on and
off for the next decade.

00:06:47.270 --> 00:06:50.200
And in that decade
you have hope, right?

00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:51.920
And then you lose your hope.

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:53.680
And you're looking
for remission,

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:54.940
and remission doesn't happen.

00:06:54.940 --> 00:06:56.920
And on and on.

00:06:56.920 --> 00:06:59.980
And we're going on and on,
too, because life has to go

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:01.150
on and on.

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:06.610
And so on and on, for my
brother, looked like--

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:10.750
this is high school prom,
Sweet Carl in the white--

00:07:10.750 --> 00:07:12.970
did everybody wear white
tuxedos in these years?

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:13.900
I don't know.

00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:16.360
He was trying to
learn how to be a man,

00:07:16.360 --> 00:07:21.490
and my dad was dying in front
of him, a very slow death.

00:07:21.490 --> 00:07:23.200
And life went on for me, too.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:29.860
I turned to my violin as,
frankly, a source of coping.

00:07:29.860 --> 00:07:31.640
It was a way to escape.

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:34.450
And my parents had their
25th wedding anniversary

00:07:34.450 --> 00:07:36.610
some here in here too.

00:07:36.610 --> 00:07:39.070
And I want to talk a little
bit about the different coping

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:40.820
mechanisms because I
think that's where it

00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:42.370
started originally going wrong.

00:07:42.370 --> 00:07:45.010
So coping for me,
yes, it was music.

00:07:45.010 --> 00:07:46.740
But I want to tell
a little story.

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:48.940
And if anybody sat in
her coaching session

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:52.450
with Sally Anderson and she asks
you what your superpower is,

00:07:52.450 --> 00:07:54.460
I know my superpower
is my ability

00:07:54.460 --> 00:07:56.530
to compartmentalize things.

00:07:56.530 --> 00:08:01.090
And a story just to illustrate
that is I wake up one morning.

00:08:01.090 --> 00:08:02.150
I'm in high school.

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:05.470
My dad is sprawled out on
the floor in what turns out

00:08:05.470 --> 00:08:09.430
to be a diabetic coma, which
is a pretty common side

00:08:09.430 --> 00:08:11.140
effect of chemotherapy.

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:12.130
We call 911.

00:08:12.130 --> 00:08:14.830
The ambulances come,
the paramedics come in,

00:08:14.830 --> 00:08:16.660
and they're trying
to talk to him,

00:08:16.660 --> 00:08:20.230
and he can't talk because he's
basically just completely out

00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:20.980
of it.

00:08:20.980 --> 00:08:22.630
And they're asking
me what his name is,

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:26.000
and I'm like Edmund
Dehnert, D-E-H-N-E-R-T.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:26.710
And I'm spelling.

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:28.573
I always have to
spell my goddamn name.

00:08:28.573 --> 00:08:29.740
Thank god I married a Moyer.

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:32.049
That's easier to
spell these days.

00:08:32.049 --> 00:08:34.515
But it was
D-E-H-N-E-R-T. Thank you.

00:08:34.515 --> 00:08:35.890
And they put him
on the stretcher

00:08:35.890 --> 00:08:38.419
and they took him off
to Evanston Hospital.

00:08:38.419 --> 00:08:42.580
And I remember then thinking OK,
I'm going to go catch the bus

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:44.390
and go to high school now.

00:08:44.390 --> 00:08:45.480
And that's what I did.

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:47.188
I got on the bus and
went to high school.

00:08:47.188 --> 00:08:49.120
I took the physics
test and I aced it.

00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:53.920
And since that day, this
ability to put tragedy over

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:57.340
on this side in
its place for when

00:08:57.340 --> 00:09:01.220
it can have time to be
addressed was very useful.

00:09:01.220 --> 00:09:04.300
And then I could go on with
the rest of my life over here.

00:09:04.300 --> 00:09:07.210
And so I find that I'm
able to really do that

00:09:07.210 --> 00:09:09.010
quite effectively.

00:09:09.010 --> 00:09:11.770
Unfortunately, my
brother was not

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:13.520
able to cope in that same way.

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:16.990
And he started turning to
alcohol in high school.

00:09:16.990 --> 00:09:18.580
By the time he went
off to college,

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:21.850
it started to be
cocaine, and eventually

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:24.130
he turned to crack
cocaine, and he really

00:09:24.130 --> 00:09:26.690
spiraled pretty far down.

00:09:26.690 --> 00:09:30.400
So at this point, the one
time Jam and I rehearsed this,

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:34.390
he said tell me more about
what Carl's relationship was

00:09:34.390 --> 00:09:37.420
like with your dad
during those years.

00:09:37.420 --> 00:09:40.090
And this image
flashed into my mind,

00:09:40.090 --> 00:09:43.360
which I shared with him the
first time, which was there

00:09:43.360 --> 00:09:44.320
was a day--

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:46.240
he was probably out of
college at this point,

00:09:46.240 --> 00:09:48.520
living in the men's
residence at the YMCA

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:52.038
in Evanston, which is not
the place you want to end up.

00:09:52.038 --> 00:09:53.830
But that's where he
was because he couldn't

00:09:53.830 --> 00:09:55.100
hold a job and pay rent.

00:09:55.100 --> 00:09:56.690
So he's at the men's residence.

00:09:56.690 --> 00:09:59.500
And he comes home and
he's ringing the doorbell,

00:09:59.500 --> 00:10:01.600
and he's ringing the
doorbell, and he's

00:10:01.600 --> 00:10:03.985
calling the house phone, and
he's ringing the doorbell.

00:10:03.985 --> 00:10:06.360
And me and my twin brother,
who were still living at home

00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:10.870
are looking at each other like
anybody gonna answer the door?

00:10:10.870 --> 00:10:16.630
And my dad's on the couch,
and he's looking sicker

00:10:16.630 --> 00:10:19.410
through the years
here, and he's starting

00:10:19.410 --> 00:10:20.850
to look like a cancer patient.

00:10:20.850 --> 00:10:25.110
And my dad goes and
answers the doorbell.

00:10:25.110 --> 00:10:27.570
And Carl's like, I can't
stay at the men's residence.

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:28.260
I can't do it.

00:10:28.260 --> 00:10:28.813
It's cold.

00:10:28.813 --> 00:10:30.480
And just let me come
in the living room.

00:10:30.480 --> 00:10:32.640
I swear I'll leave
at know 9:00, just

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:37.590
like in a mania kind of a
thing, like with a desperation.

00:10:37.590 --> 00:10:41.635
And my dad gets a blanket
and throws it on the porch

00:10:41.635 --> 00:10:43.260
and says, you can
come home when you're

00:10:43.260 --> 00:10:46.900
sober, and closes the door.

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:51.660
And me and my twin brother
were like, mmm, that was bad.

00:10:51.660 --> 00:10:56.040
And I thought of another
story, Jam, in these years.

00:10:56.040 --> 00:10:57.652
My twin brother is a DJ.

00:10:57.652 --> 00:10:59.610
And in that basement
where we all used to play,

00:10:59.610 --> 00:11:02.580
he would keep these
crates of albums.

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:05.280
One day Carl goes down there,
takes the crates of albums,

00:11:05.280 --> 00:11:07.620
goes to Howard and Western,
pawns them at the thing

00:11:07.620 --> 00:11:10.080
and sells them and goes
and gets some drugs.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:13.490
So my father found
out about this.

00:11:13.490 --> 00:11:16.120
He called us together because
of course my twin brother

00:11:16.120 --> 00:11:21.320
was like furious, and just
all kinds of anger coming out.

00:11:21.320 --> 00:11:23.498
And my dad took it
upon himself to tell us

