00:39:18.780 --> 00:39:21.870
And that relationship you have
with your brother, the words

00:39:21.870 --> 00:39:25.710
that anybody else wants to
put on his disease, that

00:39:25.710 --> 00:39:27.500
doesn't matter.

00:39:27.500 --> 00:39:29.760
So that's my first
reaction, and I love you,

00:39:29.760 --> 00:39:32.700
and you're a very
good brother to him.

00:39:32.700 --> 00:39:34.830
The second thing is--

00:39:34.830 --> 00:39:36.630
and I'm actually
curious your thought

00:39:36.630 --> 00:39:38.680
on this-- we were talking
about this yesterday.

00:39:38.680 --> 00:39:42.480
Folks were saying,
I am not bipolar.

00:39:42.480 --> 00:39:44.140
I am not an addict.

00:39:44.140 --> 00:39:47.760
I am somebody who struggles
with this disease.

00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:50.790
You called yourself a junkie.

00:39:50.790 --> 00:39:53.640
What do the words mean
for you, and how would you

00:39:53.640 --> 00:39:56.947
want somebody to talk to you?

00:39:56.947 --> 00:39:58.530
JAM ALKER: So I think
underlying that,

00:39:58.530 --> 00:40:00.630
and underlying
what you're talking

00:40:00.630 --> 00:40:09.280
about with the weight that's
put on certain words, what we're

00:40:09.280 --> 00:40:13.240
really getting at
here is stigma, right,

00:40:13.240 --> 00:40:15.520
because the words
don't necessarily

00:40:15.520 --> 00:40:20.050
matter unless there's a
negative connotation behind some

00:40:20.050 --> 00:40:22.030
of the words.

00:40:22.030 --> 00:40:25.780
So in that sense, I think it's
very important to do everything

00:40:25.780 --> 00:40:30.100
that we can to
reduce the stigma.

00:40:30.100 --> 00:40:33.970
And we do that by
doing things like this,

00:40:33.970 --> 00:40:37.703
coming and putting ourselves out
there, ripping ourselves open

00:40:37.703 --> 00:40:39.370
and being the ones
who are willing to be

00:40:39.370 --> 00:40:48.850
vulnerable to show people
we're all essentially the same.

00:40:48.850 --> 00:40:52.880
We've all got our damage.

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:54.520
We've all got our
trauma underneath.

00:40:54.520 --> 00:40:56.570
It's manifested differently
for each person.

00:40:56.570 --> 00:40:58.540
Some people, maybe,
are a little bit better

00:40:58.540 --> 00:41:00.150
at hiding it than others.

00:41:00.150 --> 00:41:03.910
But we all have that pain
to one degree or another.

00:41:03.910 --> 00:41:06.490
So yeah, you are correct.

00:41:06.490 --> 00:41:10.030
Saying I am a person
in long-term recovery,

00:41:10.030 --> 00:41:14.380
I am a person who struggles
with issues of addiction,

00:41:14.380 --> 00:41:17.770
I am a person with a
substance use disorder

00:41:17.770 --> 00:41:22.077
are the politically
correct ways of saying it.

00:41:25.740 --> 00:41:26.640
For me, I don't know.

00:41:26.640 --> 00:41:31.380
Maybe because I like to be a
dramatic storyteller, to say

00:41:31.380 --> 00:41:33.360
I was a junkie.

00:41:33.360 --> 00:41:34.110
I was.

00:41:34.110 --> 00:41:41.670
But that-- like
anything, my underlying

00:41:41.670 --> 00:41:44.520
belief in all of this is that
none of us are bad people.

00:41:44.520 --> 00:41:46.890
We are people who make
bad decisions at times.

00:41:46.890 --> 00:41:52.180
And people who are in an
addiction make bad decisions.

00:41:52.180 --> 00:41:53.510
They're not bad people.

00:41:53.510 --> 00:41:57.910
In active addiction, did I
make a lot of bad decisions?

00:41:57.910 --> 00:41:59.410
Fuck yeah.

00:41:59.410 --> 00:42:00.700
A lot.

00:42:00.700 --> 00:42:03.700
But I know I'm not a bad person.

00:42:03.700 --> 00:42:08.340
So the semantics are less
important to me than maybe

00:42:08.340 --> 00:42:09.730
to some other people.

00:42:09.730 --> 00:42:11.657
It's the same thing
with your brother

00:42:11.657 --> 00:42:12.990
who's struggling with the issue.

00:42:12.990 --> 00:42:18.390
You know, these are all
behavioral health issues,

00:42:18.390 --> 00:42:23.430
whether it's straight up mental
illness or addiction, which

00:42:23.430 --> 00:42:30.960
is a form of behavioral or
mental disease, whatever

00:42:30.960 --> 00:42:33.180
wording you want
to put behind it.

00:42:33.180 --> 00:42:34.810
But because it's
behavioral, where

00:42:34.810 --> 00:42:37.380
there are certain times
of people act out,

00:42:37.380 --> 00:42:39.528
it's looked at differently.

00:42:39.528 --> 00:42:41.820
There are people who are
like, it's the same as cancer.

00:42:41.820 --> 00:42:43.810
It should be treated
as the same as cancer.

00:42:43.810 --> 00:42:45.690
It's true to a degree.

00:42:45.690 --> 00:42:47.940
But if you had
cancer, you wouldn't

00:42:47.940 --> 00:42:50.940
go out and rob somebody for your
chemotherapy medicine, right?

00:42:50.940 --> 00:42:53.610
You wouldn't act
like a fool to be

00:42:53.610 --> 00:42:58.823
able to go out and get your
insulin if you're a diabetic.

00:42:58.823 --> 00:43:00.240
So yes, it's the
same in the sense

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:01.323
that they're all diseases.

00:43:01.323 --> 00:43:05.640
But because this is behavioral,
we can act like assholes.

00:43:05.640 --> 00:43:07.840
We could do bad things.

00:43:07.840 --> 00:43:13.260
So I just think
that it's important

00:43:13.260 --> 00:43:16.290
that what's talked about
is that underlying it,

00:43:16.290 --> 00:43:18.150
we're all good people,
we're human beings,

00:43:18.150 --> 00:43:20.730
and we need to be treated
with respect and understanding

00:43:20.730 --> 00:43:25.320
and empathy for what
we're going through.

00:43:28.857 --> 00:43:30.190
CAROLINE DEHNERT MOYER: Gregory?

