AUDIENCE: I will be there.

00:48:11.340 --> 00:48:13.007
CAROLINE DEHNERT
MOYER: You could be 38.

00:48:14.490 --> 00:48:20.100
Part of it is you setting
up your own boundaries.

00:48:20.100 --> 00:48:22.320
One of the things I
struggle with with Al-Anon

00:48:22.320 --> 00:48:27.000
is we talk about you can't
change this other person.

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:29.150
You are powerless
over their disease.

00:48:29.150 --> 00:48:35.070
And I can't totally get with
that 100% because I do think

00:48:35.070 --> 00:48:38.100
some of the things I've done
have certainly enabled him

00:48:38.100 --> 00:48:39.700
and prolonged it.

00:48:39.700 --> 00:48:43.390
Some of the other things I've
done, like say I love you,

00:48:43.390 --> 00:48:45.870
but I'm not coming to
take you to the ER today

00:48:45.870 --> 00:48:47.610
have also helped him.

00:48:47.610 --> 00:48:51.634
So I think boundaries,
am I right?

00:48:51.634 --> 00:48:53.232
JAM ALKER: Mm-hmm.

00:48:53.232 --> 00:48:54.940
CAROLINE DEHNERT MOYER:
It's really hard.

00:48:54.940 --> 00:48:56.790
I feel like if
somebody is not ready,

00:48:56.790 --> 00:48:59.405
you can't be like, why don't
you go to an AA meeting?

00:48:59.405 --> 00:49:01.530
I mean, I can tell you how
many times I tried that.

00:49:01.530 --> 00:49:05.150
I would go to an AA
meeting with you, brother.

00:49:05.150 --> 00:49:05.730
And I would.

00:49:05.730 --> 00:49:08.520
Actually, if he
asked me, I would go.

00:49:08.520 --> 00:49:13.078
But I'm not going
to drag you there.

00:49:13.078 --> 00:49:13.620
I don't know.

00:49:13.620 --> 00:49:14.870
What other advice do you have?

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:18.750
It's tough when the
person is not ready.

00:49:18.750 --> 00:49:19.590
JAM ALKER: OK.

00:49:19.590 --> 00:49:23.760
This is a great
topic, and each person

00:49:23.760 --> 00:49:25.800
is going to have their
different point of view.

00:49:25.800 --> 00:49:30.280
And I look at it, like I do
with addiction, as a spectrum.

00:49:30.280 --> 00:49:34.380
There's this idea of tough love
and this idea of soft love,

00:49:34.380 --> 00:49:36.210
and there are
consequences to either,

00:49:36.210 --> 00:49:42.330
right, that if you
engage in tough love,

00:49:42.330 --> 00:49:43.950
you still have these boundaries.

00:49:43.950 --> 00:49:45.780
I love you.

00:49:45.780 --> 00:49:47.200
Come back when you're ready.

00:49:47.200 --> 00:49:47.700
All right?

00:49:47.700 --> 00:49:50.310
So the potential
consequence to that

00:49:50.310 --> 00:49:53.490
is that they could end up
getting lost to their disease.

00:49:53.490 --> 00:49:57.158
They could end up dying
as a result of that.

00:49:57.158 --> 00:49:58.950
The other side of the
soft love is you keep

00:49:58.950 --> 00:50:00.750
providing them with things.

00:50:00.750 --> 00:50:04.640
The consequence of that is
it's enabling them, which

00:50:04.640 --> 00:50:06.240
could end up killing them.

00:50:06.240 --> 00:50:09.492
So the common
denominator here is

00:50:09.492 --> 00:50:11.200
they could end up
dying as a result of it

00:50:11.200 --> 00:50:13.950
because it's their problem.

00:50:13.950 --> 00:50:18.760
So this is about self-care,
you taking care of yourself,

00:50:18.760 --> 00:50:21.970
you deciding what you can live
with, what's best for you,

00:50:21.970 --> 00:50:27.460
and taking care of yourself and
that baby that's inside of you.

00:50:27.460 --> 00:50:30.723
Now my point of view, I
lean-- and most addicts

00:50:30.723 --> 00:50:32.140
and alcoholics who
are in recovery

00:50:32.140 --> 00:50:35.110
lean to the tough
love side of things.

00:50:35.110 --> 00:50:38.840
I wish that I had been
given less enabling.

00:50:38.840 --> 00:50:41.560
And the point is, you
tell them, I'm sorry.

00:50:41.560 --> 00:50:42.130
I love you.

00:50:42.130 --> 00:50:44.890
I'd love you to be a part
of this child's life.

00:50:44.890 --> 00:50:49.000
When you're done, and you're
ready to be sober in recovery,

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.100
come be a part of their life.

00:50:51.100 --> 00:50:54.617
That could possibly be the thing
that makes them like, shit,

00:50:54.617 --> 00:50:56.450
I do want to be a part
of this child's life.

00:50:56.450 --> 00:50:59.030
I need to do this.

00:50:59.030 --> 00:51:01.390
Maybe not.

00:51:01.390 --> 00:51:03.263
The other side of
it, in your case,

00:51:03.263 --> 00:51:04.930
kind of, from what
I'm hearing from you,

00:51:04.930 --> 00:51:06.808
is you make concessions.

00:51:06.808 --> 00:51:08.350
You let them be a
part of their life.

00:51:08.350 --> 00:51:10.373
What's the downside for them?

00:51:10.373 --> 00:51:12.540
Why would they need to
change their behavior at all?

00:51:12.540 --> 00:51:15.990
They're getting
everything they want.

00:51:15.990 --> 00:51:19.090
Consequence of the tough love,
they might say forget it,

00:51:19.090 --> 00:51:21.850
and they are not involved
in your life from that point

00:51:21.850 --> 00:51:24.020
forward.

00:51:24.020 --> 00:51:27.013
There's no easy answer.

00:51:27.013 --> 00:51:28.430
CAROLINE DEHNERT
MOYER: My brother

00:51:28.430 --> 00:51:30.800
would tell me the worst
thing you could ever

00:51:30.800 --> 00:51:33.320
do for an addict
is give them money.

00:51:33.320 --> 00:51:35.720
In other words, don't enable me.

00:51:35.720 --> 00:51:38.810
I'm going to ask you for money.

00:51:38.810 --> 00:51:40.730
Just don't give it to me.

00:51:40.730 --> 00:51:44.180
So that tough love is so hard
as the person that loves them

00:51:44.180 --> 00:51:46.440
because when I sent
that text and I said,

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:48.260
ER sounds like a good
idea if you need to.

00:51:48.260 --> 00:51:48.850
I love you.

00:51:48.850 --> 00:51:49.730
JAM ALKER: So good.

00:51:49.730 --> 00:51:52.460
CAROLINE DEHNERT MOYER: I
mean, I was dying inside.

00:51:52.460 --> 00:51:54.755
It's like, I hope he makes
it through the night.

00:51:54.755 --> 00:51:57.440
And you don't own whether
that person makes it

00:51:57.440 --> 00:51:58.477
through the night.

00:51:58.477 --> 00:52:00.060
AUDIENCE: This has
been super helpful.

00:52:00.060 --> 00:52:00.685
Thank you guys.

00:52:03.453 --> 00:52:04.870
CAROLINE DEHNERT
MOYER: All right.

00:52:04.870 --> 00:52:05.778
Hi.

00:52:05.778 --> 00:52:06.320
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:52:06.320 --> 00:52:07.940
My name is Gabby.

00:52:07.940 --> 00:52:10.010
Thank you for
sharing your stories.

00:52:10.010 --> 00:52:12.140
Really, thank you.

00:52:12.140 --> 00:52:15.850
My brother has been addicted
to heroin for about 16 years,

00:52:15.850 --> 00:52:17.900
so half of his life.

00:52:17.900 --> 00:52:20.910
And there's been a lot
of hatred between us

00:52:20.910 --> 00:52:24.170
and throughout the siblings
in the larger family.

00:52:24.170 --> 00:52:26.330
And it's been really
hard for not only

00:52:26.330 --> 00:52:30.950
me to show him that I love him,
but to feel any sense of love

00:52:30.950 --> 00:52:32.450
from him.

00:52:32.450 --> 00:52:36.020
So I just wanted to ask,
while you were struggling

00:52:36.020 --> 00:52:41.030
with your addiction, underneath
all of that addiction

00:52:41.030 --> 00:52:45.260
and disease, did you still
feel that love for your family?

00:52:45.260 --> 00:52:49.070
And in what ways were you hoping
that they could show you love?

00:52:55.180 --> 00:52:59.500
JAM ALKER: The love, I
don't think, goes away.

00:52:59.500 --> 00:53:02.890
But it is absolutely
overridden by shame.

00:53:07.270 --> 00:53:12.400
I felt, and I'm sure your
brother feels, so much shame

00:53:12.400 --> 00:53:15.250
for what he's doing
to himself and what

00:53:15.250 --> 00:53:16.420
he's doing to his family.

00:53:18.930 --> 00:53:21.180
I'm sure that the
love is not gone.

00:53:21.180 --> 00:53:26.000
I don't believe that it
has the ability to be gone.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:27.390
Love is eternal.

00:53:27.390 --> 00:53:29.200
Love is infinite.

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:30.510
It's there.

00:53:30.510 --> 00:53:33.972
It's just buried so
deep behind the shame,

00:53:33.972 --> 00:53:35.430
and oftentimes it's
that shame that

00:53:35.430 --> 00:53:37.555
keeps the cycle of addiction
going because there so

00:53:37.555 --> 00:53:38.920
much pain that goes with that.

00:53:38.920 --> 00:53:42.240
And here's the thing
with, with opiates.

00:53:42.240 --> 00:53:46.110
Opiates are physical
painkillers,

00:53:46.110 --> 00:53:50.460
but they're also
emotional painkillers.

00:53:50.460 --> 00:53:55.830
So we start to use opiates,
and that pain goes away.

00:53:55.830 --> 00:53:57.630
Not forever, temporarily.

00:53:57.630 --> 00:54:00.400
And it becomes less
and less as we go on.

00:54:00.400 --> 00:54:04.170
But I can't imagine
that it's not there.

00:54:04.170 --> 00:54:06.690
But the conflict, obviously,
from your side of things

00:54:06.690 --> 00:54:08.880
comes from the fact that
you love him so much

00:54:08.880 --> 00:54:11.010
and you want what's
best for him.

00:54:11.010 --> 00:54:14.940
And I can't be sure, but
I'd be willing to bet

00:54:14.940 --> 00:54:21.960
that from his side of things,
there is a lot of guilt, shame,

00:54:21.960 --> 00:54:24.780
remorse, self-loathing.

00:54:24.780 --> 00:54:30.420
And so that, I'm sure,
manifests in ways

00:54:30.420 --> 00:54:32.520
that appear as though
the love is gone.

00:54:32.520 --> 00:54:35.460
But I don't I don't think it is.

00:54:35.460 --> 00:54:37.620
So he's in active addiction now?

00:54:37.620 --> 00:54:38.760
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:54:38.760 --> 00:54:42.460
JAM ALKER: And is he
